<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900516-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>900516-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   McDonnell Douglas   Helicopter Co. Unit's   President Quits Post</HL><DATE>05/16/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><CO>   MD WNEWS</CO><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- William P. Brown resigned as president ofMcDonnell Douglas Helicopter Co. in the wake of the company'scontinuing poor financial performance.   The decision was announced by the company's St.Louis-based parent, McDonnell Douglas Corp. Spokesmen thereand at the helicopter company in Mesa, Ariz., refused tospeculate on the reason for the resignation, which iseffective Friday. Mr. Brown wasn't available to comment.</LP><TEXT>   McDonnell Douglas said a successor will be named in a fewweeks. Until then, William S. Ross, president of the St.Louis-based McDonnell Aircraft Co. unit, will take on theadditional duty of overseeing the helicopter company.   Mr. Brown, 57 years old, will become a consultant to theparent company and will work out of an office in the Phoenix,Ariz., area, said a spokesman for the helicopter unit. Theexecutive joined the company in 1980 as chief engineer on theArmy's Apache helicopter program before the company wasacquired by McDonnell Douglas.   Mr. Brown played an important role in smoothing thecompany's move in 1986 to Mesa from Culver City, Calif.,McDonnell Douglas said. During his tenure, he also launchedthree helicopter programs and implemented a reorganizationplan.   Last year, the helicopter company had a $137 millionwrite-off, mainly related to the Apache program, whichaccounted for about 80% of the company's revenue. InFebruary, the company said it was trimming its work force andmaking other spending cuts to improve its financialperformance and lessen the effect of reductions in defensespending.</TEXT></DOC>